\section intro Introduction
 
\b Rack is a command-line program for processing weather radar data.
It uses raw measurement data as input and generates \ref productspage  as well as \ref compositespage . 
\b Rack also provides methods for \ref andrepage . 
Quality information is supported throughout the processing chain. 
 \b Rack also supports \ref imagespage , like applying colors and transparency. 

\b Rack is based on code developed at the Finnish Meteorological
Institute since 2001. Part of the development work has been supported by the
BALTRAD project (2009-2014), see http://www.baltrad.eu .
The program can be downloaded from https://github.com/fmidev/rack .

As input, \b Rack accepts azimuthal scans - volumes or separate sweeps - 
in HDF5 files using OPERA Information Model (ODIM, http://www.eumetnet.eu/opera).
\~comment
The polar coordinate system is applied: the radar at left, 
rows presenting beams clockwise, the topmost row towards North.
\~
After loading a volume file, a typical operation is to compute a 
single-radar product. The computation is carried out in polar coordinates. 
The result can be mapped to a Cartesian products. 
The projections are calculated using the Proj4
 library (http://trac.osgeo.org/proj/).
Output files can be written in HDF5 files, PNG image files or geo-referenced GeoTIFF files.
In addition, metadata, resampled grid data and vertical profiles can be output as plain text files. 
  
 The overall data flow is illustrated below.  
  
 \dot
  digraph example {
  
      size ="12,8";
 	  rankdir=LR;
      node [shape=ellipse, fontsize=10];
      edge [color=black, fontsize=8];
	
	

	file [ label="Input file\nHDF5 (or PNG+TXT)", shape=record, URL="\ref fileiopage" color="blue"];

 	subgraph cluster2  {
	  
	  label = "Rack";
	  color = "gray";

	  volume [ label="Input volume", shape=record, URL="\ref fileiopage"];
	  
	  andre  [ label = "Anomaly detection\n and removal", URL="\ref andrepage", color="blue" ];
	  
	  polar [ label="Product generation\n(in polar coordinates)", URL="\ref productspage" color="blue"];

	  polarfile [ label="Meteorological product", URL="\ref productspage", shape=record];

	  cartesian [ label="Cartesian products\n and compositing", URL="\ref compositespage", color="blue" ];

      cartfile [ label="Cartesian product", URL="\ref compositespage", shape=record];

  	  cumulator [ label="Composite\n(Internal accumulation array)", URL="\ref compositespage", shape=record, style="dotted"];

	}

	file -> volume;
	volume -> andre -> volume;
	volume -> polar -> polarfile -> cartesian;
	volume -> cartesian [label = ""];
            
    cartesian -> cumulator [label = "add"];
    cumulator -> cartesian [label = "extract"];
    cartesian -> cartfile;
	file      -> cartfile;

    outfile [ label="Output file\nHDF5, GeoTIFF, or PNG", shape=record,  URL="\ref fileiopage" color="blue" ];

    volume -> outfile [style = "dotted"];
    polarfile -> outfile [style = "dotted"];
    cartfile -> outfile [style = "dotted"];
     
}
\enddot
  
  


 
 
 
 
 
 \section commands Usage

 \subsection command_line_format Command line arguments

A typical invocation of \b Rack looks like:
\code
rack <input-files>  <command> -o <file1>   <command2> -o <file2>  ...
\endcode

The native format for data is HDF5, but data and be read or written partially using
image and text format. See \ref fileiopage for details. 
 
Specifically, \b Rack accepts three kinds of command line arguments:
 
 -# options without arguments, like \c --help 
 -# options with arguments,  like \c --outputFile \c product.h5
 -# plain arguments recognized as input filenames, like \c volume.h5 , serving as shorthand for \c --inputFile \c \<file\> .
 
 The options are prefixed with double hyphen, "--". Some options have also a single hyphen "-", single-letter
 shorthand. (This argument syntax differs from POSIX and GNU conventions,
 e.g.  \c -x \c -y cannot be grouped to \c -xy. )
 All the arguments are handled in order; they can be thought as commands to be executed sequentially. 


Usage info and a list of commands is dumped if \c --help or \c -h or no arguments are supplied:
\code
rack --help
\endcode
The list of commands is also listed in Section \ref commands_general.
  
Help is also available for invidual commands:
\code
rack --help <command>
\endcode
 
The version of the program is displayed with \c --version.  
Other useful general commands are \c --verbose \c \<level\> and \c --status, which give
debugging information of data flow and memory.


\subsection products_brief  Meteorological products

Generation of a single-radar product is explained in section \ref productspage.
The products are generated in polar coordinates, that is, in radar's native coordinate system.  
A product may contain additional data arrays, typically quality indices or height information.
As processing and using Doppler data involves special aspects, it is handled in it own section, \ref doppler.

A product can be further converted to Cartesian coordinate system, explained next.


\subsection cartesian_brief  Converting to Cartesian images 
 
Data in polar coordinates can be mapped to a Cartesian product with \c --cCreate (abbreviated \c -c). 
The simplest possible command is
\code
rack volume.h5 --cCreate -o cartesian.h5
\endcode
which converts the first dataset (sweep) in volume.h5 to a Cartesian product.
The default projection is azimuthal equidistant, centered at the radar. The projection can be changed
with \c --cProj which uses \b Proj.4 syntax (http://trac.osgeo.org/proj/). 
The default size (bins x bins) can be changed with \c --cSize .

\code
rack volume.h5 --cSize 400,400 --cProj '+proj=stere +lon_0=25.0 +lat_0=60.000' --cCreate -o cartesian-stere.h5
\endcode

\~exec
  QUANTITY=DBZH INPUT=volume-anom-sea.h5 ./make-image-product.sh  #exec
  convert -type TrueColor ppi-DBZH.png foo.tif  
  convert +append -frame 1 foo.tif ppi-DBZH-panel.png -resize 800x400 cartesians.png 
\~


\image html  cartesians.png "Data remapped with \c --cCreate , further coloured with \c --palette , displayed with a legend generated with \c --legendOut ." 
\image latex cartesians.png "Data remapped with \c --cCreate , further coloured with \c --palette , displayed with a legend generated with \c --legendOut ." width=0.5\textwidth

The above image contains some anomalies that can be detected and removed. See \ref andrepage for details.

 
Inside \b Rack , a single-radar Cartesian product is technically similar to a radar composite -- it is a single-radar 
"composite". 
The related commands are prefixed with \c 'c'. Composite generation, projections, methods, and other options are explained 
in further detail in section \ref compositespage . 



