\subsection target Defining target data properties

The desired output storage type, scaling, and encoding can be set with \c --encoding command. 
Depending on the following command, a varying set of properties will be supported. The general form of \c --encoding command is
\code
rack <input>  --encoding <type>,<gain>,<offset>,<undetect>,<nodata>  <commands>
\endcode
and for polar products and conversions, the extended form is: 
\code
rack <input>  --encoding <type>,<gain>,<offset>,<undetect>,<nodata>,<rscale>,<nrays>,<nbins>  <commands>
\endcode

One may set one or more properties by giving only N first ones. Also \c key=value forms are supported.   
The typical choices for storage type are 'C' (unsigned char), 'S' (unsigned short int) and 'd' (double precision float). 
The next parameters \c gain and \c offset define the mapping between bit values and the physical quantity: 
\e f = \c gain * \e x + \c offset .  
In ODIM standard, \c undetect marks the data where a measurement value falls under a sensitivity limit and 
\c nodata marks areas where no measurement at all is available.
Also grid geometry (\c nbins , \c nrays and \c rscale ) can be set when applicable.
For example, producing a polar product (here 500m CAPPI, see \ref productspage) with some desired properties is given by:
\code
  rack volume.h5 --encoding C,0.4,-20,rscale=1000,nbins=250  --pCappi 500 -o cappi-500.h5
\endcode
\b Rack provides default encodings for some quantities. The configuration can be listed and changed with
\c --quantityConf command.

As to hierarchical structure of resulting products, the default location of computed meteorological products and Composites is 
\c /dataset1/data1 . Any previous results are overwritten. This can be changed by means of \c --append command: one can 
combine several products in same \c dataset group, adding a new \c data group, or append a new \c dataset group. 

For modifying existing data, see \ref modifypage .


\subsection quantityConf Default encoding of quantities

Measurement parameters in radar have a varying scale. For example, DBZH is typically between -32dBZ and 50dBZ whereas
RHOHV ranges between 0.0 and 1.0. Further, different storage types can be used, and the resulting value range 
should be compatible with the encoding. In some cases, like in creating radar image composites, \b Rack can
use predefined storage types and encoding. The following examples illustrate the usage

\code
rack --quantityConf DBZ:S          # for encoding dBZ, use unsigned short int, with default scaling
rack --quantityConf DBZ:C,0.6,-30  # for encoding dBZ, use unsigned char, with gain=0.5 and offset=-32
\endcode

The arguments can be named explicitly, as in the case of \c --select and \c --encoding .
The encoding of a given quantity is displayed if the quantity is issued without type specifier character.
A quantity can be also assigned \c zero, a "virtual" physical small value to be applied instead of \c undetect marker.

\code
rack --quantityConf 'DBZ'
\endcode
\~exec
rack --quantityConf 'DBZ' > quantityConf.inc
\~
yelding
\include quantityConf.inc
where asterisk \c * marks the current default storage type and scaling.

The full list of predefined quantity encodings are listed with
\code
rack --quantityConf ''
\endcode
One may freely add encodings simply by setting them with \c --quantityConf


